  "chunk_index": 11,
  "summary": "Jimmy Scegesh informs Lorel and Bondel of his discovery regarding Gerry Wade. He believes Gerry, who appears to be an unremarkable Foreign Office employee, is actually a high-ranking member of a secret intelligence agency. Jimmy notes that Gerry was not in Britain during the war and speaks German fluently, leading Jimmy to conclude that the Seven O'Clock Club is an international criminal organization. To investigate, Jimmy plans to attend an upcoming party hosted by George Lomax. Bondel suggests that Jimmy use Bill, George's assistant, to gain entry by posing as a wealthy playboy interested in politics. Bondel intends to meet Bill the following evening to secure a guest list. Jimmy insists that Lorel stay out of the operation to avoid suspicion, a directive she accepts with an obedience that Bondel finds suspicious.\n\nFollowing the meeting, Bondel visits Scotland Yard to consult Inspector Bartlett, a detective who handles political cases. She inquires about secret organizations headquartered in the Seven Clocks area, but Bartlett claims the area has been rebuilt into an upper-class residential zone and no longer hosts such groups. Bondel attempts to probe further by mentioning the recent death of Ronny DeFleur and noting that DeFleur mentioned a \"seven o'clock clock\" before dying. She also brings up George Lomax’s recent visit regarding a threatening letter marked with the Seven Dials symbol. Bartlett remains uncooperative and dismissive, ultimately advising Bondel to stop investigating the matter.",
